{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568602"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.09,0.33,0.12,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108080"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5064"},{"type":"tags","id":"5100"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44565"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108080"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for preoperative assessment before an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy scheduled in nine days. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, dyslipidaemia, and diabetic nephropathy with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (60-90). Her diabetes was diagnosed eight years ago. Her current medications are empagliflozin, metformin, and weekly semaglutide (last dose two days ago). Her most recent glycated haemoglobin was 7.5% (\u0026lt;6.0) (58 mmol/mol [\u0026lt;42]).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m\u00b2. She has no peripheral oedema, and her cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe surgeon has requested advice regarding perioperative management of her diabetes medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate perioperative medication management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Withhold empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery, continue semaglutide","Delay surgery until semaglutide withheld for at least 5 weeks, then withhold empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery","Withhold semaglutide immediately, empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery","Withhold empagliflozin for one day before and including day of surgery, continue semaglutide and metformin until the night before surgery","Withhold semaglutide immediately, continue metformin and empagliflozin until two days before and including day of surgery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question addresses the perioperative management of diabetes medications, with particular focus on the risk of euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis (EDKA) associated with sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitors and current guidelines regarding glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptor agonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery, continue semaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan. SGLT2 inhibitors like empagliflozin should be withheld for two days before surgery and on the day of surgery to minimize the risk of EDKA in people with diabetes. Metformin can be safely continued until the night before surgery but should be withheld on the day of surgery. According to current ANZCA guidelines, GLP-1 receptor agonists should be continued throughout the periprocedural period other than being omitted day of procedure due to risks of hyperglycaemia in people with diabetes and may compromise weight control for people taking it for this indication. There are various anaesthetic techniques that can be used to overcome the risks associated with delayed gastric emptying on these medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay surgery until semaglutide withheld for at least 5 weeks, then withhold empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as it is overly cautious, compromises timely care, and risks rebound hyperglycaemia and weight gain with discontinuation of semaglutide with poses additional perioperative risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold semaglutide immediately, empagliflozin for two days before and including day of surgery, continue metformin until the night before surgery\u003C/strong\u003E correctly manages the SGLT2 inhibitor but unnecessarily withholds semaglutide. Current evidence and ANZCA guidelines do not support routine cessation of GLP-1 receptor agonists before elective procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold empagliflozin for one day before and including day of surgery, continue semaglutide and metformin until the night before surgery\u003C/strong\u003E provides insufficient time for empagliflozin clearance (should be two days) and fails to address the need to withhold metformin on the day of surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold semaglutide immediately, continue metformin and empagliflozin until two days before surgery\u003C/strong\u003E unnecessarily withholds semaglutide according to current guidelines and fails to properly manage empagliflozin, which should be withheld for two days before surgery, not just until two days before.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SGLT2 inhibitors should be withheld for two days before surgery and on the day of surgery due to risk of euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis.","GLP-1 receptor agonists should not be routinely withheld before elective procedures according to current ANZCA guidelines.","Metformin can be continued until the night before surgery but should be withheld on the day of surgery."],"references":["Australian Diabetes Society and Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists. ADS-ANZCA Perioperative Diabetes and Hyperglycaemia Guidelines (Adults). November 2022. Available at: https://www.diabetessociety.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/ADS-ANZCA-Perioperative-Diabetes-and-Hyperglycaemia-Guidelines-Adults-November-2022-v2-Final-3.pdf","Australian Diabetes Society, National Association of Clinical Obesity Services, Gastroenterological Society of Australia, Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists. Clinical Practice Recommendations regarding patients taking GLP-1 receptor agonists and dual GLP-1/GIP receptor co-agonists prior to anaesthesia or sedation for surgical and endoscopic procedures. April 2025. Available at: https://www.anzca.edu.au/getContentAsset/0f35028e-e371-4220-a49a-ddee877051c8/80feb437-d24d-46b8-a858-4a2a28b9b970/Clinical-Practice-Recommendations-Periprocedural-GLP-1RA-use-Apr-2025.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T12:34:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T13:13:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14110"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108080"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"